PART A: What's Our Model?
¶

The Original Formula for the Fama French Model Is¶

Where:¶

  • R_it is the total return of a stock or portfolio, i at time t;
  • R_ft is the risk free rate of return at time t;
  • R_Mt is the total market portfolio return at time t;
  • R_it - Rft is expected excess return;
  • R_Mt - Rft is the excess return on the market portfolio (index);
  • SMB_t is the size premium (small minus big); and
  • HML_t is the value premium (high minus low).
  • β_1,2,3 refer to the factor coefficients.

Our Model¶

  • For our Three-Factor Model, we change the third factor into the ln(Volume_it).
  • The new formula is shown as belowed:

Note that,¶

  • ln(Volume_it) is the third factor, measuring the trading activity;

Why Volume?¶

For the Trading Activity:¶

  • Volume is the number of shares or contracts traded in a security or an entire market during a given period of time.
  • It's an important indicator to measure the relative worth of a market move. If the markets make a strong price movement, then the strength of that movement depends on the volume for that period. The higher the volume during the price move, the more significant the move.
  • We except this variable can measure how active the stock is traded and contribute to our model as the third factor.

Variable Selection¶

For the risk free rate of return:¶

  • The 1-month Treasury Bill rate is selected to represent the risk free rate.
  • Note that The 1-month Treasury Bill rate measures the return rate of one year.

Variable Selection¶

For the size premium (small minus big):¶

  • This variable is constructed basen on the market cap to represent the effect of market cap.
  • We notice that the individual market weights level of each component stocks of the S&P 500 have already been calculated based on their market cap to construct the index, so it's obvious that Market Weight Level of Stock_i is proportional to its Market Cap:

So it's convenient for us to use the individual market weights of each component stocks to divide them into 'Big' and 'Small' group and label them.¶

Step 1. Scrap Data¶

  • Defined a fuction named 'dataScraping' to scrap the stock data from Yahoo Finance and a piece of code to get the 1-mon treasury return data and market index data, then save it.
  • Note that:
    • Subject to the website, we can only get 100 days of data step by step;
    • The last row is supposed to be excluded;
    • Subject to the unstable Internet, we should only get 50 stocks data or may lead to unexpected error.

# function to scrap the stock data
def dataScraping(data_list, start_date, end_date):    
    yahoo_finance_url = 'https://au.finance.yahoo.com/quote/%s/history?period1=%s&period2=%s&interval=1d&filter=history&frequency=1d'
    df_list = []
    count = 0
    one_hundred_epoch = 60 * 60 * 24 * 100      # used to get 100 days of data step by step    
    for data in data_list:
        print("Scraping", data, "...")
        # try to get web page if end_date > start_date
        first_round = True
        temp_date   = end_date
        while temp_date > start_date:
            yahoo_hist_price_page = rq.get(yahoo_finance_url % (data, start_date, temp_date))
            if yahoo_hist_price_page.status_code == 200:
                if first_round:
                    # exclude last row
                    df_list.append(pd.read_html(yahoo_hist_price_page.text)[0].iloc[:-1]) 
                    first_round = False
                else:
                    df_combined = pd.read_html(yahoo_hist_price_page.text)[0].iloc[:-1]
                    # more efficient way to combine
                    df_list[count] = pd.concat([df_list[count], df_combined], axis=0)     

            else:
                raise Exception('Some Error Happened. Http Error Code %d' % yahoo_hist_price_page.status_code)
            temp_date = str(int(temp_date) - one_hundred_epoch)
        count += 1
    print("----------------------\nScraping process done!")    
    return df_list

for year in years:

        new_month_df = pd.DataFrame()

        new_month_df['Month Rate'] = bill_rate_df['4 WEEKS']['BANK DISCOUNT']

        new_month_df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(new_month_df['Date'])        
        # concat two dataframe

# Function: change format date into epoch time
def dateToEpoch(date):
    time_tuple = time.strptime(date, '%Y-%m-%d')
    time_epoch = time.mktime(time_tuple)
    time_tostr = str(int(time_epoch))
    
    return time_tostr

# Function: used to cleaning data
def dataCleaning(df_list, data_list):
    for i in range(len(df_list)):
        for column in df_list[i].columns:
            if column == 'Date':
                continue
            df_list[i][column] = pd.to_numeric(df_list[i][column], errors='coerce')
        # Drop duplicated data
        df_list[i].drop_duplicates(["Date"], keep="first", inplace=True)
        # Add security name as a column
        df_list[i]['Name'] = str(data_list[i])
        # Convert time format
        df_list[i]['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df_list[i]['Date'])
        # Merge risk-free rate by Date
        df_list[i] = pd.merge(df_list[i], bill_rate_month_df, how='inner', on=['Date'])
        # Reverse dataframe
        df_list[i] = df_list[i][::-1]
        # Reset index
        df_list[i] = df_list[i].reset_index(drop=True)

# Feature Engineering

for i in range(len(market_index_df)):
    market_index_df[i]['Pct_change'] = market_index_df[i]['Adj. close**'].pct_change(periods = 1)
    market_index_df[i]['Rm - Rf'] = market_index_df[i]['Pct_change'] - stocks_df[0]['Month Rate'].shift() / 100 / 365

for i in range(len(stocks_df)):
    
    # Ri of stocks
    stocks_df[i]['Pct_change'] = stocks_df[i]['Adj. close**'].pct_change(periods = 1)
    # Ri - Rf of stocks
    stocks_df[i]['Ri - Rf'] = stocks_df[i]['Pct_change'] - stocks_df[0]['Month Rate'].shift() / 100 / 365
    # Log volume
    stocks_df[i]['Log_Volume'] = np.log(stocks_df[i]['Volume'])
    
    # Rmkt - Rf from market_index, used sp500
    stocks_df[i] = pd.merge(stocks_df[i], market_index_df[0][['Date', 'Rm - Rf']], how='inner', on=['Date'])

Step 3. Data Pre-process¶

We should get the following variables for each time t and stock i, and then merge and save them:¶

  • Get 'Ri - Rf'
  • Get 'Rm - Rf'
  • Get 'Rs - Rb'
  • Get 'Log_Volume'

Note that:¶

  • There are another two portfolios (classified as Ri) which contains energy and technology industry, and the two lists are shown as below:
    energy_list = ['XOM','CVX','COP','KMI','SLB','PSX','EOG','OXY','VLO','MPC','OKE','WMB','BHGE','PXD','HES']
tech_list   = ['MSFT','AAPL','GOOG','GOOGL','FB','INTC','CSCO','ORCL','ADBE','CRM','ACN','IBM','TXN','AVGO','NVDA']
  • 1-month treasury rate should be divided by 100, for real percentage, and 365, for a single day, to get Rf.
  • We should log the variable Volume to make it reasonable.
  • We also standardised all the variables to do the regression.

Step 4. Do the regression¶

Defined new functions to regress those selected variables, which will return:¶

  • Each model coefficients (β) and parameter （α）, to get the regression equation;
  • t-statistics and p-values for each β, to tell us if they are significant;
  • R squared, to tell us the fitting effect of our model.

Then think how to explain the result.¶

# Do the regression and save information
score_list = []
name_list  = []
F1_list = []
F2_list = []
F3_list = []
P_F1_list = []
P_F2_list = []
P_F3_list = []
factor_list = ['Rm - Rf', 'Rs - Rb', 'Log_Volume']
for stock in stocks_df:    
    # drop rows contain nan
    stock.dropna(axis=0, inplace=True)
    X_train = stock[factor_list]
    Y_train = stock['Ri - Rf']    
    if stock.shape[0] <= 0:
        continue    
    # data standardised
    scaler = StandardScaler()    
    for factor in factor_list:
        X_train[factor] = scaler.fit_transform(X_train[factor].values.reshape(-1,1))
    Y_train = scaler.fit_transform(Y_train.values.reshape(-1,1))    
    # fit linear regression model 
    reg = LinearRegression(normalize=True, n_jobs=4).fit(X_train, Y_train)    
    # Save information
    score_list.append(reg.score(X_train, Y_train))
    name_list.append(stock['Name'][-1:].values[0])
    F1_list.append(reg.coef_[0, 0])
    F2_list.append(reg.coef_[0, 1])
    F3_list.append(reg.coef_[0, 2])
    P_F1_list.append(reg.p[0, 0])
    P_F2_list.append(reg.p[0, 1])
    P_F3_list.append(reg.p[0, 2])

PART D: How to Explain?
¶

Regression Result¶

Regression in two different industries: energy and technology¶

  • Stocks of energy companies: XOM, CVX, COP, KMI, SLB, PSX, EOG, OXY, VLO, MPC, OKE, WMB, BHGE, PXD, HES
  • Stocks of technology companies: MSF, AAPL, GOOG, GOOGL, FB, INTC, CSCO, ORCL, ADBE, CRM, ACN, IBM, TXN, AVGO, NVDA

Regression Result¶

Regression of energy industry¶

Note that, average R²= 0.382073¶

Regression of technology industry¶

Note that, average R²=0.523144¶

For Instance: Stock MSFT(Microsoft)¶

Conclusion 1¶

  • average β_1 of energy industry = 0.546518;
  • average β_2 of energy industry = 0.107293;
  • average β_3 of energy industry = 0.009819;
  • In energy industry，excess return is expected to increase by 0.55% for Market Risk Premium (X1: Rm-Rf) increase by 1%; excess return is expected to increase by 0.1% for Market Cap factor (X2: SMB) increase by 1%; excess return is expected to increase by 0.01% for Volume factor (X3: ln(Volume)) increase by 1%;

Conclusion 2¶

  • average β_1 of technology industry = 0.716680;
  • average β_2 of technology = -0.071826;
  • average β_3 of technology = -0.042392;
  • In technology industry, excess return is expected to increase by 0.52% for Market Risk Premium (X1: Rm-Rf) increase by 1%; excess return is expected to decrease by 0.07% for Market Cap factor (X2: SMB) increase by 1%; excess return is expected to decrease by 0.04% for Volume factor (X3: log(Volume)) increase by 1%;

Conclusion 3¶

  • Average R² of energy industry = 0.382073
  • Average R² of technology industry = 0.523144
  • Average R² of energy industry = 0.382073 < Average R² of technology industry = 0.523144， which shows that Market Risk Premium (X1: Rm-Rf), Market Cap factor (X2: SMB) and Volume factor (X3: ln(Volume)) have more explanations for the excess return of stocks in technology industry than for the excess return of stocks in energy industry；

Conclusion 4¶

  • average β_2 of energy industry = 0.107293 > 0;
  • average β_3 of energy industry = 0.009819 > 0;
  • average β_2 of technology = -0.071826 < 0;
  • average β_3 of technology = -0.042392 < 0;
  • So Market Cap factor (X_2: SMB) and Volume factor (X_3: log(Volume)) have positive impacts on the excess return of stocks in energy industry, however, these two factors have negative impacts on the excess return of stocks in technology industry.
